				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">There is only one audio channel on the NES for &quot;digital output&quot; (i.e. raw digital samples).  It's been called many different things over the years: DPCM, PCM, DMC.  There is no consistency, sorry to say.  Technically <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-code_modulation" class="postlink">PCM</a> is technically the &quot;sample format&quot; of the data, although to be more precise it's <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_modulation" class="postlink">DPCM</a> (delta pulse code modulation).<br /><br />I certainly expect a sperglord to show up and pee all over the above information.  *braces self*<br /><br />The <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/APU#DMC_.28.244010-4013.29" class="postlink">APU DMC</a> can only read sample data from $C000-FFFF.  It cannot read data from any other location.  So I do not see how it would be possible for the game to be playing digital audio from content that is located in $A000-BFFF; the APU DMC cannot do this.<br /><br />Punch Out! uses <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/MMC2" class="postlink">MMC2</a>, where the last 3 PRG banks are hard-wired to $A000-FFFF; only $8000-9FFF is &quot;changeable&quot;.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

