				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Well, technically the DMC <em>can</em> read samples outside of $C000-$FFFF, but only when exploiting address overflows. It cannot start a sample outside $C000-$FFFF, but if the DMC reads a sample and it's going past $FFFF, <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/APU_DMC#Memory_reader" class="postlink">then the address will oddly wrap at $8000</a>. This can be done e.g. by starting a sample at $FFC0 and configuring a sample to be more than $40 samples i.e. writing $FF to $4012 and writing &gt;$03 to $4013.<br /><br />...but that's a corner case, and that's not that useful to know here <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" />. I don't know that game but the sample must be located at run time somewhere in $C000-$FFFF, maybe you're wrongly interpreting the address where you've found the sample? Punch-Out!! has 128KB PRG-ROM, the sample must be located in the last 16K of it, so in the .nes file, the offset in byte should be between 0x0001C010 and 0x00020010.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

